.TH "ORKTREE\-PATH" "1" "2025" "orktree" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
orktree\-path \- print orktree workspace path
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]orktree path\f[R] \f[I]branch\f[R] [\f[B]\[en]from\f[R] \f[I]base\f[R]] [\f[B]\[en]no\-git\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Print the workspace path for the given orktree.
If the orktree does not exist, it is created automatically.
If the orktree is not mounted, it is mounted.
.PP
Use \f[B]\-\f[R] to print the source root path.
.PP
This command is used internally by shell integration.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[I]branch\f[R]
The branch name, orktree ID, or unique prefix.
.TP
\f[B]\-\f[R]
Print the source root path.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]from\f[R], \f[B]\-f\f[R] \f[I]base\f[R]
Branch or git ref to base the new orktree on.
Only used when auto\-creating.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]no\-git\f[R]
Skip git worktree setup when auto\-creating.
.TP
\f[B]\[en]help\f[R], \f[B]\-h\f[R]
Print usage information.
.SH EXAMPLES
Print the workspace path:
.IP
.EX
orktree path fix\-parser
.EE
.PP
Print the source root:
.IP
.EX
orktree path \-
.EE
.PP
Use in a script:
.IP
.EX
cd \[dq]$(orktree path fix\-parser)\[dq]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
\f[B]orktree\f[R](1), \f[B]orktree\-switch\f[R](1)
